<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>bash on ELL Blog</title><link>https://blog.elijahlopez.ca/tags/bash/</link><description>ELL Blog (bash)</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Mon, 14 Feb 2022 14:06:30 -0500</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://blog.elijahlopez.ca/tags/bash/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Bash &amp; Linux Helpers</title><link>https://blog.elijahlopez.ca/posts/bash-helpers/</link><pubDate>Mon, 14 Feb 2022 14:06:30 -0500</pubDate><guid>https://blog.elijahlopez.ca/posts/bash-helpers/</guid><description>&lt;p>It seems that many article tutorials on &lt;code>bash&lt;/code> are ugly, are suboptimal, and are no straight forward.
My goal is for this file to be a reference file whenever I need to do scripting after a long time.
One important concept in bash, is that an exit code of 0 indicates True, not False. Which seems counterintuitive if you program in
any non-scripting language like C/C++ or Python.&lt;/p>
